The introduction of combination antiretroviral therapy (cART) drastically 
improved performance status, immune function, and life expectancy of 
HIV-infected individuals. In addition, incidence of opportunistic infections and 
of AIDS-defining malignancies declined. Nevertheless, aggressive non-Hodgkin's 
lymphoma still remains the leading cause of AIDS-related deaths. The 
availability of cART, however, significantly improved the therapeutic options 
for HIV-positive patients with lymphomas. Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, 
Burkitt's lymphoma, or Hodgkin lymphoma has increasingly become curable 
